<subSubSection id="E9AF48D2BF5FFF9F1D95FBBD99D3FAEA" pageId="2" pageNumber="253" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A10A1B59BF5FFF9F1D95FBBD99D3FAEA" blockId="2.[151,1437,901,1575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF5FFF9F1D95FBBD9974FBCD" bold="true" box="[199,322,1081,1107]" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Medium sized (TL: 
<quantity id="664DB6BCBF5FFF9F1F67FBBD9AF5FBCA" box="[565,707,1081,1108]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1" metricValueMax="5.3" metricValueMin="4.9" pageId="2" pageNumber="253" unit="mm" value="5.1" valueMax="5.3" valueMin="4.9">4.9–5.3 mm</quantity>
), oblong-oval species. Head with testaceous clypeus, frons and vertex usually darkened, brown; pronotum orange-brown to dark brown, laterally broadly testaceous; elytra brown with testaceous lateral sides and broad basal testaceous band not reaching suture. Pronotum with short longitudinal strioles laterally. Each elytron with six complete discal striae and one submarginal stria: striae 1–5 beginning at base and ending close to apex, odd striae somewhat longer than even ones; stria 6 shorter, absent at base and ending at apical fourth; submarginal stria rather short, presenting only in third fourth of elytral length (
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF5FFF9F19E1FB699CC3FA99" box="[1203,1269,1261,1287]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="31.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[192,1390,187,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@31.[190,1398,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Habitus of Copelatus in China. 1. C. bacchusi (♂; Xishuangbanna, Yunnan); 2. C. chinensis (♂; Lankeshan, Zhejiang); 3. C. chinensis (holotype ♀ of C. collocallosus); 4. C. dentatipenis sp. nov. (holotype ♂; Jinggangshan, Jiangxi). Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6410698" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6410698/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view weakly sickle-shaped with apex slightly skewed on ventral side (
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF5FFF9F19EEFA959D24FAB5" box="[1212,1298,1297,1323]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–38" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1819,1843]" captionTargetBox="[204,1387,192,1774]" captionTargetId="figure-23@38.[190,1398,181,1795]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 29–38. Male genitalia of Copelatus. 29, 31, 33, 35, 37. median lobe in lateral view; 30, 32, 34, 36, 38. paramere. 29–30. C. bacchusi (Hainan); 31. C. chinensis (a. Lakeshan, Zhejiang; b. Yanjiajie, Hunan; c. Tainmushan, Zhejiang); 32. C. chinensis (Tianmushan, Zhejiang); 33. C. dentatipenis sp. nov. (a. holotype, Jinggangshan, Jiangxi; b. Guadun, Fujian; c. Mangshan, Hunan); 34. C. dentatipenis sp. nov. (holotype, Jinggangshan, Jiangxi); 35–36. C. felicis sp. nov. (holotype, Baishui, Yunnan); 37. C. diversistriatus sp. nov. (a. holotype, Pu’er, Yunnan; aa. detail of lateral carina with spines; b. Attapeu, Laos; c. NE Mintaingbin Forest Camp, Myanmar); 38. C. diversistriatus sp. nov. (holotype, Pu’er, Yunnan). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6411116" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6411116/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). Parameres slender, ‘C’-shaped; apex short and broad; apical lobes long, club-shaped (
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF5FFF9F1E85FAB19C1DFAD1" box="[983,1067,1333,1359]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–38" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1819,1843]" captionTargetBox="[204,1387,192,1774]" captionTargetId="figure-23@38.[190,1398,181,1795]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 29–38. Male genitalia of Copelatus. 29, 31, 33, 35, 37. median lobe in lateral view; 30, 32, 34, 36, 38. paramere. 29–30. C. bacchusi (Hainan); 31. C. chinensis (a. Lakeshan, Zhejiang; b. Yanjiajie, Hunan; c. Tainmushan, Zhejiang); 32. C. chinensis (Tianmushan, Zhejiang); 33. C. dentatipenis sp. nov. (a. holotype, Jinggangshan, Jiangxi; b. Guadun, Fujian; c. Mangshan, Hunan); 34. C. dentatipenis sp. nov. (holotype, Jinggangshan, Jiangxi); 35–36. C. felicis sp. nov. (holotype, Baishui, Yunnan); 37. C. diversistriatus sp. nov. (a. holotype, Pu’er, Yunnan; aa. detail of lateral carina with spines; b. Attapeu, Laos; c. NE Mintaingbin Forest Camp, Myanmar); 38. C. diversistriatus sp. nov. (holotype, Pu’er, Yunnan). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6411116" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6411116/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). Female similar to male, strioles on pronotum more numerous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9AF48D2BF5FFF9F1D95FAF99AE2F9B9" pageId="2" pageNumber="253" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="A10A1B59BF5FFF9F1D95FAF99AE2F9B9" blockId="2.[151,1437,901,1575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF5FFF9F1D95FAF99957FA09" bold="true" box="[199,353,1405,1431]" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species was described, and for 40 years known only from the Uttarakhand State in northern India. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation id="C52466A8BF5FFF9F1C18FA259A09FA25" author="Shaverdo, H. &amp; Wewalka, G. &amp; Stastny, J. &amp; Hendrich, L. &amp; Fery, H. &amp; Hajek, J." box="[330,575,1441,1468]" pageId="2" pageNumber="253" pagination="179 - 196" refId="ref33554" refString="Shaverdo, H., Wewalka, G., Stastny, J., Hendrich, L., Fery, H. &amp; Hajek, J. (2021) New records of diving beetles and corrections updating the Catalogue of Palearctic Dytiscidae (Coleoptera). Aquatic Insects, 42 (2), 179 - 196. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650424.2021.1903509" type="journal article" year="2021">
Shaverdo 
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF5FFF9F1CEBFA2699DEFA25" box="[441,488,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">et al</emphasis>
. (2021)
</bibRefCitation>
provided additional records not only from Bhutan and Nepal in the Himalayan Region, but also from Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam, suggesting that 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF5FFF9F1EE4FA429C0FFA41" authorityName="Wewalka" authorityYear="1981" box="[950,1081,1477,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bacchusi">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF5FFF9F1EE4FA429C0FFA41" box="[950,1081,1477,1504]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">C. bacchusi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread in the continental southeast Asia. The present records from two distant Chinese provinces confirm this statement. 
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF5FFF9F1993FA6D9A52F9B9" bold="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">
First records from 
<collectingCountry id="D9A25BC9BF5FFF9F1DC5F98998D6F9B9" box="[151,224,1549,1575]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="6371D5BBBF5FFF9F1DA3F989997CF9B9" box="[241,330,1549,1575]" country="China" name="Hainan" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">Hainan</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="6371D5BBBF5FFF9F1CD1F98999D7F9B9" box="[387,481,1549,1575]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
provinces)
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF5FFF9F1F26F9899AF1F9B9" box="[628,711,1549,1575]" captionStart="FIGURE 81" captionStartId="43.[151,250,2008,2032]" captionTargetBox="[229,1358,1062,1978]" captionTargetId="figure-47@43.[224,1364,1054,1983]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 81. Map of distribution of Copelatus in China Mainland." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6411120" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6411120/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="253">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
